    "solution": "y - 4x + 3 = 0\n\nWhen y = 0, 0 - 4x + 3 = 0\n\nThen -4x = -3\n\nx = 3/4\n\nSo the line cuts the x-axis at point (3/4, 0).\n\nWhen x = 0, y - 4(0) + 3 = 0\n\nThen y + 3 = 0\n\ny = -3\n\nSo the line cuts the y-axis at the point (0, -3)\n\nHence the midpoint of the line y - 4x + 3 = 0, which lies between the x-axis and the y-axis is;\n\n[1/2(x<sub>1</sub> +x<sub>2</sub> ),1/2(y<sub>1</sub> +y<sub>2</sub> )]\n\n\n[1/2(3/4+0),1/2(0+−3)]\n\n\n[1/2(3/4),1/2(−3)]\n\n\n[3/8,−3/2]",
    "examtype": "utme",
